    <h1 class="text-center mb-4">Antenatal & Postnatal Care</h1>
    <p class="text-center mb-5">Comprehensive guide to care before, during, and after pregnancy.</p>
    
    <div class="row align-items-center">
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <h2>The Importance of Maternal Care</h2>
        <p>Quality antenatal and postnatal care are crucial for the health and wellbeing of both mother and baby. Regular check-ups, proper nutrition, and appropriate medical interventions can prevent complications and ensure the best possible outcomes for pregnancy and the postpartum period.</p>
        <p>Antenatal care (also called prenatal care) begins when you find out you're pregnant and continues until delivery, while postnatal care covers the period from childbirth to about six weeks after delivery.</p>
        <p>Both stages involve physical check-ups, emotional support, screening tests, and education about pregnancy, childbirth, breastfeeding, and newborn care.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-6">
        <img src="https://pixabay.com/get/gd332fa1551c82553caa33b469802ddbb0cfcbe5da922357b2674368a1ee5613dc19fc094733aa284b5b422bef2ada60e7cb9bd954e42803bd0aa98726aaadf81_1280.jpg" alt="Prenatal Check-up" class="img-fluid rounded">
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Antenatal Care</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto mb-5">
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">When to Start Antenatal Care</h4>
            <p>It's recommended to begin antenatal care as soon as you know you're pregnant, ideally within the first 12 weeks. Early care allows for:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Accurate dating of the pregnancy</li>
              <li>Early detection of risk factors</li>
              <li>Timely screening tests</li>
              <li>Guidance on nutrition and lifestyle adjustments</li>
              <li>Management of any pre-existing medical conditions</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">First Trimester (Weeks 1-12)</h4>
            <h5>Recommended Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Initial prenatal visit (comprehensive assessment)</li>
              <li>Follow-up visit around 12 weeks</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>What to Expect:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Medical history review</li>
              <li>Physical examination</li>
              <li>Blood tests (blood type, hemoglobin, infections)</li>
              <li>Urine tests</li>
              <li>Dating ultrasound</li>
              <li>Discussion about prenatal genetic screening options</li>
              <li>Nutrition and lifestyle counseling</li>
              <li>Prescription for prenatal vitamins</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Common Concerns:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Morning sickness</li>
              <li>Fatigue</li>
              <li>Food aversions</li>
              <li>Breast tenderness</li>
              <li>Frequent urination</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Second Trimester (Weeks 13-27)</h4>
            <h5>Recommended Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Every 4 weeks (more frequently for high-risk pregnancies)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>What to Expect:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Regular monitoring of weight and blood pressure</li>
              <li>Urine tests</li>
              <li>Fetal heartbeat check</li>
              <li>Measurement of fundal height</li>
              <li>Anatomy ultrasound (18-22 weeks)</li>
              <li>Glucose screening test (24-28 weeks)</li>
              <li>Discussion about childbirth options</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Common Concerns:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Back pain</li>
              <li>Round ligament pain</li>
              <li>Constipation</li>
              <li>Swelling in extremities</li>
              <li>Skin changes (melasma, linea nigra)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Third Trimester (Weeks 28-40+)</h4>
            <h5>Recommended Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Weeks 28-36: Every 2-3 weeks</li>
              <li>Weeks 36-delivery: Weekly</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>What to Expect:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Continued monitoring of weight and blood pressure</li>
              <li>Urine tests</li>
              <li>Fetal heartbeat check</li>
              <li>Measurement of fundal height</li>
              <li>Assessment of fetal position</li>
              <li>Group B Streptococcus screening (35-37 weeks)</li>
              <li>Discussion about labor signs and when to go to the hospital</li>
              <li>Review of birth plan</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Common Concerns:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Shortness of breath</li>
              <li>Heartburn</li>
              <li>Braxton Hicks contractions</li>
              <li>Sleep difficulties</li>
              <li>Increased urination</li>
              <li>Anxiety about labor and delivery</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Nutrition During Pregnancy</h4>
            <p>Proper nutrition is essential for the health of both mother and developing baby. Key recommendations include:</p>
            <h5>Daily Nutritional Needs:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Additional 340-450 calories (2nd and 3rd trimesters)</li>
              <li>Protein: 75-100g</li>
              <li>Calcium: 1000mg</li>
              <li>Iron: 27mg</li>
              <li>Folate: 600-800mcg</li>
              <li>Omega-3 fatty acids: 200-300mg DHA</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Foods to Include:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Colorful fruits and vegetables</li>
              <li>Whole grains</li>
              <li>Lean proteins (meat, poultry, fish, eggs, legumes)</li>
              <li>Dairy products or calcium-fortified alternatives</li>
              <li>Healthy fats (avocados, nuts, olive oil)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Foods to Limit or Avoid:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Raw or undercooked meat, poultry, eggs, and seafood</li>
              <li>High-mercury fish</li>
              <li>Unpasteurized dairy products and juices</li>
              <li>Raw sprouts</li>
              <li>Excessive caffeine</li>
              <li>Alcohol</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Preparing for Childbirth</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Birth Plan</h4>
            <p>A birth plan is a document that outlines your preferences for labor and delivery. While birth doesn't always go as planned, having your wishes documented can help guide your care team.</p>
            <h5>What to Include:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Who you want present during labor and delivery</li>
              <li>Preferences for pain management (medication, epidural, natural techniques)</li>
              <li>Position preferences for labor and delivery</li>
              <li>Atmosphere preferences (lighting, music, quiet)</li>
              <li>Preferences for fetal monitoring</li>
              <li>Views on interventions (induction, episiotomy, forceps)</li>
              <li>Immediate postpartum wishes (skin-to-skin, delayed cord clamping)</li>
              <li>Feeding plans for baby</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Remember to discuss your birth plan with your healthcare provider and be flexible, as medical needs may necessitate changes.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Childbirth Education</h4>
            <p>Childbirth classes can help you prepare for labor, delivery, and early parenthood. Options include:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Lamaze:</strong> Focuses on natural birth with relaxation and breathing techniques</li>
              <li><strong>Bradley Method:</strong> Partner-coached natural childbirth</li>
              <li><strong>HypnoBirthing:</strong> Uses self-hypnosis and deep relaxation</li>
              <li><strong>Hospital-based classes:</strong> Cover basics of labor, delivery, and often include hospital tours</li>
              <li><strong>Breastfeeding classes:</strong> Preparation for nursing your baby</li>
              <li><strong>Newborn care classes:</strong> Basic baby care skills</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Most classes are taken in the third trimester, though some comprehensive programs start earlier. Online options are increasingly available as well.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Packing for the Hospital</h4>
            <h5>For Labor and Delivery:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Photo ID and insurance information</li>
              <li>Birth plan (multiple copies)</li>
              <li>Comfortable clothes for labor</li>
              <li>Socks, slippers, or warm footwear</li>
              <li>Lip balm and hair ties</li>
              <li>Massage tools or comfort items</li>
              <li>Music or media devices with chargers</li>
              <li>Camera</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>For Your Hospital Stay:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Nursing bras and breast pads</li>
              <li>Toiletries and personal care items</li>
              <li>Comfortable going-home outfit</li>
              <li>Phone and charger</li>
              <li>Snacks for you and your partner</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>For Baby:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Approved car seat (installed correctly)</li>
              <li>Going-home outfit (weather appropriate)</li>
              <li>Swaddle blanket</li>
              <li>Hat</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Signs of Labor</h4>
            <h5>Early Labor Signs:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Lightening (baby dropping lower in pelvis)</li>
              <li>Increased Braxton Hicks contractions</li>
              <li>Nesting instinct (sudden energy burst and desire to prepare)</li>
              <li>Loss of mucus plug</li>
              <li>Slight weight loss</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>When to Call Your Provider:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Regular contractions (5-1-1 rule: contractions 5 minutes apart, lasting 1 minute, for 1 hour)</li>
              <li>Water breaking (clear fluid leaking or gushing)</li>
              <li>Bright red bleeding (more than spotting)</li>
              <li>Decreased fetal movement</li>
              <li>Severe headache or visual changes</li>
              <li>Severe abdominal pain</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="alert alert-info">
              <strong>Note:</strong> Always follow your provider's specific guidance about when to call or go to the hospital, especially if you have a high-risk pregnancy.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Postnatal Care</h2>
    
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Physical Recovery</h4>
            <p>Regardless of delivery method, your body needs time to heal after childbirth. Recovery typically includes:</p>
            <h5>After Vaginal Delivery:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Vaginal discharge (lochia) for 2-6 weeks</li>
              <li>Perineal soreness (especially with tears or episiotomy)</li>
              <li>Afterpains as uterus contracts</li>
              <li>Breast changes and milk production</li>
              <li>Initial urinary or bowel difficulties</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>After Cesarean Delivery:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Incision pain and healing</li>
              <li>Limited mobility initially</li>
              <li>Same vaginal discharge as vaginal birth</li>
              <li>Possible gas pain from surgery</li>
              <li>Longer overall recovery time (typically 6-8 weeks)</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Self-Care Tips:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Rest whenever possible</li>
              <li>Accept help from family and friends</li>
              <li>Stay hydrated and eat nutritious foods</li>
              <li>Use prescribed pain relief as needed</li>
              <li>Follow specific aftercare instructions for perineal care or C-section incision</li>
              <li>Do gentle postpartum exercises when cleared by your provider</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Emotional Wellbeing</h4>
            <p>The postpartum period brings significant hormonal shifts and lifestyle changes that can affect your emotional health:</p>
            <h5>Baby Blues:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Affects up to 80% of new mothers</li>
              <li>Symptoms include mood swings, anxiety, irritability, crying, and feeling overwhelmed</li>
              <li>Typically begins 2-3 days after delivery and resolves within two weeks</li>
              <li>Usually improves with rest, support, and self-care</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Postpartum Depression (PPD):</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>More severe and persistent than baby blues</li>
              <li>Affects 10-20% of new mothers</li>
              <li>Symptoms include persistent sadness, extreme fatigue, difficulty bonding with baby, thoughts of harming yourself or the baby, withdrawal from family and friends</li>
              <li>Requires professional treatment (therapy, medication, or both)</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="alert alert-warning">
              <strong>Important:</strong> If you experience symptoms of postpartum depression, seek help from your healthcare provider promptly. This is a medical condition, not a personal failing, and effective treatments are available.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Breastfeeding Basics</h4>
            <p>Breastfeeding provides optimal nutrition for babies and offers health benefits for mothers, but it can come with a learning curve.</p>
            <h5>Benefits for Baby:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Perfect nutrition that changes to meet baby's needs</li>
              <li>Antibodies that boost immune system</li>
              <li>Reduced risk of infections, allergies, and certain chronic diseases</li>
              <li>Easier digestion than formula</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Benefits for Mother:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Promotes bonding with baby</li>
              <li>Helps uterus contract and reduce bleeding</li>
              <li>Burns extra calories</li>
              <li>Reduces risk of breast and ovarian cancer, type 2 diabetes, and postpartum depression</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>Getting Started:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Initiate breastfeeding within the first hour after birth if possible</li>
              <li>Ensure proper latch to prevent nipple pain</li>
              <li>Feed on demand (8-12 times per 24 hours for newborns)</li>
              <li>Learn to recognize hunger cues</li>
              <li>Consider meeting with a lactation consultant if you encounter challenges</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="col-md-6 mb-4">
        <div class="card h-100">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h4 class="card-title">Postpartum Check-ups</h4>
            <p>Postpartum medical care is essential for monitoring your recovery and addressing any concerns:</p>
            <h5>Standard Schedule:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>First check:</strong> 1-3 weeks after birth (earlier for C-section or complications)</li>
              <li><strong>Comprehensive postpartum visit:</strong> 4-6 weeks after birth</li>
              <li><strong>Additional visits:</strong> As needed for specific concerns</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>What to Expect at Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Physical examination</li>
              <li>Assessment of incision or perineal healing</li>
              <li>Screening for postpartum depression</li>
              <li>Discussion of birth control options</li>
              <li>Breastfeeding support</li>
              <li>Review of any pregnancy or birth complications</li>
              <li>Guidance on returning to physical activity</li>
            </ul>
            <h5>When to Call Between Check-ups:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li>Fever over 100.4°F (38°C)</li>
              <li>Heavy bleeding (soaking through a pad in less than an hour)</li>
              <li>Severe pain</li>
              <li>Redness, swelling, or discharge from incisions</li>
              <li>Difficulty breathing or chest pain</li>
              <li>Severe headache or changes in vision</li>
              <li>Thoughts of harming yourself or the baby</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    
    <div class="accordion" id="maternalFAQ">
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
          <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
            How much weight should I gain during pregnancy?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#maternalFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p>Recommended weight gain depends on your pre-pregnancy BMI:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Underweight (BMI less than 18.5):</strong> 28-40 pounds</li>
              <li><strong>Normal weight (BMI 18.5-24.9):</strong> 25-35 pounds</li>
              <li><strong>Overweight (BMI 25-29.9):</strong> 15-25 pounds</li>
              <li><strong>Obese (BMI 30 or more):</strong> 11-20 pounds</li>
            </ul>
            <p>For twin pregnancies, the recommended gain is higher. Weight gain should be gradual, with most occurring in the second and third trimesters. Discuss your specific needs with your healthcare provider, as individual circumstances may warrant different recommendations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
            Is it safe to exercise during pregnancy?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#maternalFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p>For most women with uncomplicated pregnancies, exercise is not only safe but beneficial. The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity per week during pregnancy.</p>
            <p><strong>Safe exercises include:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Walking</li>
              <li>Swimming and water workouts</li>
              <li>Stationary cycling</li>
              <li>Modified yoga and Pilates (pregnancy-specific classes)</li>
              <li>Low-impact aerobics</li>
              <li>Strength training with appropriate modifications</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Exercises to avoid:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Activities with high fall risk (skiing, horseback riding)</li>
              <li>Contact sports</li>
              <li>Exercises that involve lying flat on your back after the first trimester</li>
              <li>Hot yoga or hot Pilates</li>
              <li>Scuba diving</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Always get clearance from your healthcare provider before starting or continuing an exercise program during pregnancy, especially if you have any complications or health concerns.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
            When will my period return after childbirth?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#maternalFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p>The return of menstruation after childbirth varies among women and depends on several factors:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>If not breastfeeding:</strong> Periods typically return 4-8 weeks after delivery</li>
              <li><strong>If breastfeeding:</strong> Periods may not return until breastfeeding frequency decreases, often when supplementary foods are introduced or the baby begins sleeping longer at night</li>
              <li><strong>Exclusively breastfeeding:</strong> Some women don't have periods until they completely wean their baby</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Important notes:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>You can ovulate before your first postpartum period, so pregnancy is possible even before menstruation returns</li>
              <li>If you want to prevent pregnancy, discuss contraception options with your provider at your postpartum visit</li>
              <li>Your first few cycles after childbirth may be irregular or different from your pre-pregnancy periods</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If your period hasn't returned by 3 months postpartum (if not breastfeeding) or if you have concerns about your menstrual cycle, consult your healthcare provider.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
            How do I know if my baby is getting enough breast milk?
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFour" data-bs-parent="#maternalFAQ">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p>It can be challenging to measure how much breast milk your baby is consuming, but there are several indicators that your baby is getting enough:</p>
            <h5>Signs of adequate intake:</h5>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Wet diapers:</strong> 5-6+ wet diapers per day after day 5</li>
              <li><strong>Bowel movements:</strong> At least 3-4 per day in the first month (may decrease after 6 weeks)</li>
              <li><strong>Weight gain:</strong> Returns to birth weight by 10-14 days and gains approximately 4-7 ounces per week thereafter</li>
              <li><strong>Feeding frequency:</strong> 8-12 feedings per 24 hours</li>
              <li><strong>Contentment:</strong> Generally seems satisfied after feedings</li>
              <li><strong>Alert and active:</strong> Good tone, color, and alertness when awake</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If you're concerned about your baby's intake, consult with a lactation consultant or your pediatrician. They can weigh your baby before and after a feeding to measure milk transfer or help address any breastfeeding challenges you're experiencing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

